caption: Absolutely amazing service, despite the gale-force hurricane winds. The omakase? HOT DIGGITY. : chef's kiss: Go here, get great sushi, leave happy.

Best sushi I've had in Chicago by miles. Of note, the specialty rolls were inventive enough to be a unique experience without detracting from the subtle flavors of the fish itself. Omakase was amazing and we're looking forward to trying what they have to offer on the menu next time.

Sushi was 5 stars, no doubt. Special roll was so smooth, excellent quality.  Food was above average (tiger shrimp and calamari). Private tents with little buddy heaters was pretty romantic and felt Covid-19 safe and actually quite comfortable (even in 16 degree weather). Also got Yuzu mocktails which were spring-y and fresh. Eat in the outdoor tents if u can, it’s fun

Tanoshii has great fresh fish options if you’re into it. The fish and chips is amazing. Their non-traditional take on the rolls is something worth trying where the chef takes some creative liberty and uses ingredients that are rarely used in sushi rolls. We went for the full omakase with chef’s recommendations. While the flavors hit the right marks, it would’ve been nice to have a bit more variety in the rolls.
Very good and fresh sushi. Only four stars because of being on the higher price spectrum of the sushi scale.
Sushi and Bar restaurant.

My now husband and I went here after our small wedding on November 14th to enjoy our first 'date night' together as husband and wife. We did the Omakase, which I would highly recommend, which was a chef's choice meal.  We are adventurous eaters, but I am allergic to eel and they more than complied. The fish was fresh, the appetizers prepared and explained and they never once implied us leaving, after we sat there for a littttle too long. Our server brought out sake she thought we would enjoy, made recommendations on sashimi and nigiri and was just so attentive and personable.  In regards to COVID, they have these little mini-huts outside with heaters and a door. We will absolutely be back, this was the best sushi we have had in awhile.

Great sushi and warm individual shelters for up to 4 with your own heaters! Was here in the low 40's with a strong wind and dined without a jacket. Much warmer than those big tents. Not to mention great cocktails, sushi and service!

They have these igloos that don’t seem like they would be warm but they do the job! It’s 43-degrees out but we are toasty. Aside from that- the food here has always been exceptional. The service is 5-stars. This family owned and operated restaurant is truly a gem. I’ve been a regular for years and can’t say enough great things about their hospitality, service and cuisine. Visit them!!
Amazing experience for date night!  Food was incredible!  I highly recommend!

This has been a traumatizing experience. I don’t recommend this place for anybody. I’d rather eat sushi from jewel Osco or Mariano’s than here. On top of the food being terrible, I found hair in the sushi. Worst sushi ever.

Ordered the omakase experience, overall felt overpriced for the number/quality of dishes. My favorite was the seared bluefin appetizer. The fish and chips and scallop were good but one-note.

While they slightly overdo it with the sauces, avocado, and truffle, it's always absolutely delicious.  This is really a 4.6+ star review because I wish you could actually up the price and quality (maybe simplicity?) of the omakase on demand.  Their base omakase is excellent - and nails it for American tastes. I just wish I could get more of the Michelin worthy dressed Nigiri they do as the highlight of the omakase.  Maybe they can have two tiers on their menu - one around $50-$75 like normal, and one more around $125 if you want to just let the chef not worry about filler courses and just deliver quality. They have the fish - and the skill to serve it.  Really tough to leave here unhappy - and incredibly consistent. Been here 15+ times and never left unsatisfied.

Very understaffed or undertrained. These are not true sushi chefs. Half the restaurant is empty but it’s a 20 minute wait because of a lack of servers and kitchen capacity. 6 dedicated sushi chefs and it takes over 30 minutes to make the chefs special roll, which still managed to arrive before the salad and nigiri. The VERY expensive nigir averaging $12 for 2 pieces was some of the smallest pieces I have ever seen- both rice and fish.  I just don’t get it. There is no reason to be here. Head down the street to Umai for way better quality and larger portions at cheaper prices.  Edit: almost forgot about the horror story of overhearing the sushi chefs realize the wrong order went to the wrong table but it’s basically “the same thing” multiple times...
They offer an awesome variety of delicious food. I loved dining here. Employees are always kind, rates are convenient and the spot is always kept clean.

This is by far the best sushi in Chicago hands down. My boyfriend and I stumbled across this place by chance and fell in love with it. Then we couldn’t figure out where we had gone for a while and found it again and their menu had changed slightly but it was still the delicious sushi place we had been to before. The fish there is just so fresh tasting. The combinations of flavors they put in their rolls are amazing. I absolutely love this place and we go back there at least once every time my boyfriend is in town. HIGHLY recommend.

The omakase, which leaves your maki roll makeup up to the chef, is a must try, I've never been disappointed by it and I've been to 3 locations in the area and probably a total of 10 times.

One of the worst services I’ve ever had at a restaurant!! We ordered Miso soup and a few roles to start, 20 minutes went by and the sushi came so I asked the waiter, Cohen P if he forgot the soup and he said no and wanted to check on the soup but since the food was already there we said to forget about it. He didn’t apologize and just walked away. Then we realized one of the three rolls was incorrect but the the server never came by to check on us so after finally coming by we told him the roll was incorrect and he again did not apologize and actually shook his head as he walked off. I just hope he was having a bad day and that he is not normally like this. I don’t even remember how the food was bc I was so furious w the service. Definitely never going back there again!

An overpriced lunch here left me colder than Chicago winter. The rice was al dente but also bland, cold, dry, and packed like a stone. The fish was crudely sliced, cold, and devoid of flavor. At least it was fresh. The only acceptable seafood was the sea urchin (clean flavor, rich, and aromatic) but was letdown by soggy seaweed.  I did enjoy the refreshing coedo beer.  Service-wise, I sat at the sushi bar but the chef did not acknowledge me once. He was busy chatting with the waitress. Maybe that’s why he forgot how to mold the sushi into any discernible form.  Lastly, the restaurant itself was styled like a black lacquered box. A shiny coffin if you will.  Overall, there wasn’t anything to recommend. I will not return.

I am a sushi person, and this is some of the best sushi I've had. They don't really have a menu. Instead, everything is Omakase or "chef's choice". Not only is this a great way to try new stuff, but it allows dinner conversation to really flow as you're not debating what to get. Instead you just relax and have an awesome meal. Will be returning soon!

As a vegetarian, I usually don't even consider going to many sushi places since some aren't very accommodating. Tanoshii is a fantastic exception to this. I came here recently with friends and asked our waiter for three vegetarian rolls, whatever the chef felt like making. The chef prepared three very different options that were all amazing. One was sweet potato, one was avocado, and another had a few veggies that were absolutely delicious. The presentation of them was gorgeous as well. Definitely recommend this spot.

Came here with a large group for a birthday and had an excellent experience, from the food to the service.  Definitely start off with one of their specialty drinks. I have finally gotten to the point in my sushi habit where I can trust the chef, which turns out is a great thing since Tanoshii specializes in Omakase - which in Japanese means "i'll leave it to you" and is all about entrusting the Chef.  The waiter asked if we had any dietary restrictions, explained that Chef Mike visits the fish market every day and hand selects the freshest fish and designs his menu daily based on those factors. They do not serve soy sauce (although i am sure they would if you asked) rather each slice if fish is accompanied with it's own seasonal sauce - and all were delicious. It is a welcome addition the West Loop, lots of natural light, sleek decor and a knowledgeable staff.
